No, come on, stop it. Six weeks ago, Elon Musk  signed a merger agreement i=
n which he made a legally binding promise to=C2=A0buy Twitter Inc. for $54.=
20 per share. A few weeks later, he decided he didn=E2=80=99t want to pay $=
54.20 per share anymore, perhaps because he had grown=C2=A0bored of Twitter=
, or=C2=A0perhaps=C2=A0because the prices of social-media stocks, and of Mu=
sk=E2=80=99s company Tesla Inc., had fallen, and $54.20 looked pretty expen=
sive.The merger agreement does not, however, allow Musk to walk away becaus=
e he changed his mind. He needed some pretext for walking away. He  came up=
 with what he thought was a good one: Twitter says, in its public filings, =
that no more than 5% of its =E2=80=9Cmonetizable daily active users=E2=80=
=9D are =E2=80=9Cfalse or spam=E2=80=9D accounts, and Musk has a vague sens=
e that there are more spam bots than that. (To be fair, a lot of his=C2=A0f=
ollowers are bots.) He floated the idea that he could walk away from the de=
al because Twitter was lying about the spam bots.To a non-lawyer I suppose =
this looked like a good pretext, but it was not. It was not for at least th=
ree reasons:=09Musk had not a shred =E2=80=94=C2=A0not even the tiniest bit=
 =E2=80=94=C2=A0of evidence that Twitter=E2=80=99s estimates are wrong, and=
 it  seems very likely that they are right.[1]=09Even if Twitter=E2=80=99s=
=C2=A0estimates are wrong, Musk could not get out of the merger agreement u=
nless the error was likely to have a =E2=80=9Cmaterial adverse effect=E2=80=
=9D on Twitter=E2=80=99s business, and it absolutely would not.=09Musk has =
been talking about Twitter=E2=80=99s bot problem forever, and in fact he or=
iginally said that he wanted to buy Twitter in order to=C2=A0fix the bot pr=
oblem, so no one could possibly believe him when he said that he wanted to =
walk away from the deal because he just discovered that Twitter has a bot p=
roblem.So there were a few days when everyone talked about how Musk was try=
ing to back out of the agreement, and about what Twitter could do to stop h=
im, and then that died down=C2=A0when everyone realized that this pretext w=
as terrible.I  wrote at the time:While Musk has tweeted about not going ahe=
ad with the deal, and talked about it at a private conference for his fans,=
 it doesn=E2=80=99t seem like he has sent any formal notice to Twitter sayi=
ng that the deal is off. (Certainly neither Musk nor Twitter have made any =
SEC filings about that sort of notice, which you might expect if he=E2=80=
=99d sent one.) Perhaps his lawyers are less willing to ignore the agreemen=
t than he is, or at least need a better pretext than he=E2=80=99s managed s=
o far.Well. I guess he set his lawyers =E2=80=94 led by Mike Ringler of Ska=
dden, Arps, Slate, Meagher & Flom LLP =E2=80=94=C2=A0to work finding a pret=
ext that they could stomach. And they found one, and today they filed it wi=
th the US Securities and Exchange Commission, in the form of a letter to Tw=
itter threatening to call off the deal.Their pretext is sort of the lawyer =
version of Musk=E2=80=99s pretext. The problem, say the lawyers, is=C2=A0no=
t that Twitter has too many spam bots. The problem is that, when Musk asks =
for information=C2=A0about the spam bots, Twitter doesn=E2=80=99t give him =
the information he wants. From their letter:Twitter has, in fact, refused t=
o provide the information that Mr. Musk has repeatedly requested since May =
9, 2022 to facilitate his evaluation of spam and fake accounts on the compa=
ny=E2=80=99s platform. Twitter=E2=80=99s latest offer to simply provide add=
itional details regarding the company=E2=80=99s own testing methodologies, =
whether through written materials or verbal explanations, is tantamount to =
refusing Mr. Musk=E2=80=99s data requests. Twitter=E2=80=99s effort to char=
acterize it otherwise is merely an attempt to obfuscate and confuse the iss=
ue. Mr. Musk has made it clear that he does not believe the company=E2=80=
=99s lax testing methodologies are adequate so he must conduct his own anal=
ysis. The data he has requested is necessary to do so.There is a technical =
bit of mergers-and-acquisitions lawyering here that might be worth explaini=
ng. In the merger agreement, Twitter makes=C2=A0representations, statements=
 about its business that it promises are=C2=A0true. Arguably one of them is=
 something to the effect of =E2=80=9Cnot much more than 5% of our monetizab=
le daily active users are spam bots.=E2=80=9D[2] Musk thinks, or says he th=
inks, that this representation is not true. But even if he=E2=80=99s right,=
 he can=E2=80=99t get out of the deal, unless it is untrue and would have a=
 =E2=80=9Cmaterial adverse effect=E2=80=9D on Twitter=E2=80=99s business. I=
f in fact 90% of Twitter=E2=80=99s users are bots, it knows that, and it ha=
s been lying to advertisers for years, then, uh, sure, maybe. But in any pl=
ausible case, there will not be an MAE, so=C2=A0he still has to close the d=
eal and pay $54.20 per share. Merger agreements are written this way so tha=
t buyers can=E2=80=99t change their minds and come up with some trivial pre=
text =E2=80=94=C2=A0some tiny error in the representations =E2=80=94=C2=A0t=
o get out of the deal.But in the merger agreement, there are also=C2=A0cove=
nants, promises that Musk and Twitter make to each other about what they wi=
ll do going forward, between the signing of the merger agreement and the cl=
osing. If Twitter breaches a=C2=A0representation, Musk still has to close u=
nless the breach causes a material adverse effect.[3]=C2=A0But if Twitter b=
reaches a=C2=A0covenant, Musk can walk away: He doesn=E2=80=99t have to clo=
se unless Twitter =E2=80=9Cshall have performed or complied, in all materia=
l respects, with its obligations required under this Agreement.=E2=80=9D[4]=
 There is no MAE requirement: You just have to comply with the covenants.An=
d one of the=C2=A0covenants=C2=A0is that Twitter =E2=80=9Cshall ... furnish=
 promptly to [Musk] all information concerning the business, properties and=
 personnel of [Twitter] as may reasonably be requested in writing, in each =
case, for any reasonable business purpose related to the consummation of th=
e transactions contemplated by this Agreement.=E2=80=9D[5] Another one is t=
hat Twitter will =E2=80=9Cprovide any reasonable cooperation reasonably req=
uested=E2=80=9D in connection with Musk=E2=80=99s debt financing.[6]Musk, a=
s a non-lawyer, came up with a pretext that is like =E2=80=9CTwitter told m=
e something untrue about its bot problem, so I can walk away.=E2=80=9D That=
 sounds like it might work, but doesn=E2=80=99t work. But Musk=E2=80=99s=C2=
=A0lawyers=C2=A0have a better pretext. It=E2=80=99s something like =E2=80=
=9Ckeep asking them for more information about their bot problem; eventuall=
y you=E2=80=99ll ask questions they won=E2=80=99t answer, and=C2=A0then=C2=
=A0you can walk away.=E2=80=9DSo they write:Under various terms of the merg=
er agreement, Twitter is required to provide data and information that Mr. =
Musk requests in connection with the consummation of the transaction. =E2=
=80=A6 Mr. Musk is entitled to seek, and Twitter is obligated to provide, i=
nformation and data for, inter alia, =E2=80=9Cany reasonable business purpo=
se related to the consummation of the transaction=E2=80=9D (Section 6.4). T=
witter must also provide reasonable cooperation in connection with Mr. Musk=
=E2=80=99s efforts to secure the debt financing necessary to consummate the=
 transaction, including by providing information =E2=80=9Creasonably reques=
ted=E2=80=9D by Mr. Musk (Section 6.11). ...As Twitter=E2=80=99s prospectiv=
e owner, Mr. Musk is clearly entitled to the requested data to enable him t=
o prepare for transitioning Twitter=E2=80=99s business to his ownership and=
 to facilitate his transaction financing. To do both, he must have a comple=
te and accurate understanding of the very core of Twitter=E2=80=99s busines=
s model=E2=80=94its active user base.=C2=A0And then they threaten that Musk=
 will walk away if he doesn=E2=80=99t get the information he wants:Based on=
 Twitter=E2=80=99s behavior to date, and the company=E2=80=99s latest corre=
spondence in particular, Mr. Musk believes the company is actively resistin=
g and thwarting his information rights (and the company=E2=80=99s correspon=
ding obligations) under the merger agreement. This is a clear material brea=
ch of Twitter=E2=80=99s obligations under the merger agreement and Mr. Musk=
 reserves all rights resulting therefrom, including his right not to consum=
mate the transaction and his right to terminate the merger agreement.The le=
tter does not say what information Musk wants=C2=A0=E2=80=94=C2=A0it refere=
nces previous letters, dated May 25 and May 31, asking for the information,=
 but those have not been made public =E2=80=94=C2=A0but it makes it clear t=
hat Musk is not looking for information about how Twitter came to its concl=
usion that fewer than 5% of monetizable daily active users are bots. He is =
not looking to understand or test Twitter=E2=80=99s methodology. Instead, h=
e wants to =E2=80=9Cconduct his own analysis,=E2=80=9D which I would think =
would require=C2=A0raw data about Twitter=E2=80=99s users. Last month Twitt=
er Chief Executive Officer Parag Agrawal tweeted a thread about how Twitter=
 does this analysis, noting that=C2=A0Twitter =E2=80=9Cuses both public and=
 private data (eg, IP address, phone number, geolocation, client/browser si=
gnatures, what the account does when it=E2=80=99s active=E2=80=A6) to make =
a determination.=E2=80=9D Presumably if Musk wants to =E2=80=9Cconduct his =
own analysis,=E2=80=9D he will want the same sorts of identifiable private =
data that Twitter uses.Again, I don=E2=80=99t know exactly what he=E2=80=99=
s asking for, but in general I can understand why Twitter would be nervous =
about sharing user data with Musk. For one thing, there are all sorts of re=
gulatory and risk reasons to be nervous about sharing user data with someon=
e who, for now at least, does not work at Twitter. For another thing, Musk =
has been publicly trolling Twitter about the bot problem, and about everyth=
ing else, for weeks now, and there=E2=80=99s no reason to think he would be=
 particularly responsible with=C2=A0this=C2=A0information. His lawyers writ=
e:Mr. Musk will of course comply with the restrictions provided under Secti=
on 6.4, including by ensuring that anyone reviewing the data is bound by a =
non-disclosure agreement, and Mr. Musk will not retain or otherwise use any=
 competitively sensitive information if the transaction is not consummated.=
But this is not much comfort, because Musk has constantly ignored the restr=
ictions of the merger agreement, including by  tweeting disparaging things =
about Twitter.=C2=A0He himself has boasted publicly that he violated a non-=
disclosure agreement with Twitter by tweeting about Twitter=E2=80=99s bot m=
ethodology![7]=C2=A0If you give him sensitive user data he is just absolute=
ly going to tweet about it, and trusting his promises not to would be dumb.=
 And if he does break his promises, what can Twitter do? Sue him to call of=
f the deal? Twitter doesn=E2=80=99t want to call off the deal. Musk does!St=
ill, this pretext is better than Musk=E2=80=99s pretext, for at least three=
 reasons:=09As closing conditions for the merger, representations are quali=
fied by MAE, but covenants by =E2=80=9Cin all material respects.=E2=80=9D I=
f Twitter does not comply with its covenants, Musk=C2=A0can=C2=A0walk away,=
 so this makes for a good threat.=09The representations are limited to what=
 the merger agreement actually says, but this covenant =E2=80=94=C2=A0the o=
ne about furnishing information =E2=80=94=C2=A0is limited only by (1) Musk=
=E2=80=99s (and his lawyers=E2=80=99) imagination and (2) the somewhat fuzz=
y standard of =E2=80=9Cany reasonable business purpose related to the consu=
mmation of the transactions.=E2=80=9D[8] So Musk can ask Twitter, like, =E2=
=80=9Cgive me the cell phone numbers of every one of your monetizable daily=
 active users so I can call them and see if they=E2=80=99re bots,=E2=80=9D =
and Twitter will have to decide if that is reasonable, if it violates any l=
aws, etc. If they say no, Musk can disagree, and it might end up in court, =
with Musk having the ability to walk away if he wins. If they say yes, Musk=
 can just keep asking for more things. =E2=80=9CTell us what all of your us=
ers were thinking about last Thursday,=E2=80=9D why not.=09Because Musk rea=
lly has been talking about=C2=A0solving=C2=A0the bot problem, and because t=
his request can be characterized as helping him do that, it doesn=E2=80=99t=
 sound as much like a lie as his pretext does. =E2=80=9CAs Twitter=E2=80=99=
s prospective owner, Mr. Musk is clearly entitled to the requested data to =
enable him to prepare for transitioning Twitter=E2=80=99s business to his o=
wnership,=E2=80=9D says the letter: If he=E2=80=99s going to clean up the b=
ots, he needs information about the bots, and he is allowed to ask for it n=
ow.I mean, to be clear, it isn=E2=80=99t=C2=A0a=C2=A0good=C2=A0pretext. It =
is, for instance, very hard to imagine that Musk=E2=80=99s banks are clamor=
ing for detailed information about spam accounts to line up their financing=
; Twitter has raised debt financing in the past with its existing bot discl=
osure. Nor is it clear what Musk=E2=80=99s =E2=80=9Creasonable business pur=
pose related to the consummation of the transactions=E2=80=9D is. And becau=
se it is so clearly part of Musk=E2=80=99s broader trolling operation, it i=
s hard to imagine him=C2=A0winning=C2=A0if this ends up in court: If he ref=
uses to close because Twitter won=E2=80=99t humor his bot-fishing expeditio=
n, it seems unlikely that a Delaware court will side with him. But it does =
raise the risk=C2=A0for Twitter,=C2=A0which gives him a bit more leverage t=
o try to renegotiate the price. It is all going to get so much dumber.In ot=
her Twitter M&A news, on Friday the deal=C2=A0cleared US antitrust review w=
ith no problems. One possibility is that Musk will keep sending nasty lette=
rs and tweets about bots, and the people =E2=80=94=C2=A0including the ones =
working for him =E2=80=94=C2=A0whose job it is to get the deal done will ke=
ep working to get the deal done, and one day Musk will be mid-sentence typi=
ng a nasty tweet about Twitter and find out that he owns it.
