      Revlon
   =20
 =20
In 2020, Citigroup Inc. accidentally paid off $900 million of Revlon Inc.=
=E2=80=99s debt. Citi was the administrative agent on a Revlon loan, it was=
 doing a restructuring transaction for Revlon, it hit the wrong button and =
paid off the loan out of its own money. Oops! It asked for the money back, =
but for a variety of unusual reasons many of the lenders refused. So Citi s=
ued them, and last year, in a somewhat shocking decision, a judge  said the=
y could keep the money. Citi appealed, and might still win =E2=80=94=C2=A0t=
he appeal is still pending =E2=80=94=C2=A0but for now Citi is out about $50=
0 million.=C2=A0One strange aspect of this case is that =E2=80=A6=C2=A0nobo=
dy knows what happened to the loan? Citi just paid people $500 million for =
no reason, which is hard to fit into conventional analyses of how debt work=
s. Like:=09Does Revlon still owe the original lenders that $500 million, ev=
en though Citi already paid them? (After all,=C2=A0Revlon=C2=A0didn=E2=80=
=99t pay them.)=09Does Revlon owe Citi=C2=A0that $500 million? After all, C=
iti did Revlon the (completely unasked-for) favor of paying off its loan fo=
r it, so surely Revlon owes Citi something for that.=09Does Revlon not owe =
the money to anyone? Is that $500 million debt gone?I suppose this will be =
clarified at some point, but the problem is perhaps becoming more urgent:Co=
smetics maker Revlon Inc. has begun talks with lenders ahead of looming mat=
urities of debt to try to steer the business clear of bankruptcy, according=
 to people familiar with the matter.A group of lenders including Angelo Gor=
don, Glendon Capital Management LP and King Street Capital Management are i=
n restructuring discussions with Revlon about pushing out the due date on r=
oughly $1.7 billion in debt that matures as early as 2024, people familiar =
with the matter said. =E2=80=A6The continuing debt talks are at early stage=
s, coming more than a year before the company=E2=80=99s next significant ma=
turity in September 2023.The 2023 loan is held by a separate group of lende=
rs that were accidentally paid off by the loan=E2=80=99s agent bank, Citigr=
oup Inc., in a back-office blunder, but who then gave the money back at the=
 bank=E2=80=99s request. Others kept roughly $500 million of the mistaken p=
ayment and remain locked in litigation with Citi. =E2=80=A6If Citibank lose=
s its appeal, it also could seek repayment of the loan from Revlon by the S=
eptember 2023 maturity date, a person familiar with the matter said. But Ci=
ti=E2=80=99s legal rights to seek repayment on the loans at maturity are mu=
rky, other people said.=C2=A0We have talked=C2=A0around here about  the bas=
ic move in modern distressed-debt investing, which is for a company to extr=
act value from some lenders and give some of it to other lenders in exchang=
e for them approving the transaction. If you have $2 billion of debt, you p=
romise holders of $1.1 billion of the debt that you will pay them 105 cents=
 on the dollar, and in exchange they approve a transaction where you give t=
he holders of the other $900 million zero: The majority lenders get a bonus=
, the minority lenders get stiffed, and you get to reduce your debt. It doe=
sn=E2=80=99t work exactly that way =E2=80=94=C2=A0that is schematic and ove=
rsimplified =E2=80=94=C2=A0but that=E2=80=99s the right starting point for =
thinking about these things.Here, uh, Citi has a vague $500 million moral c=
laim against Revlon? You could imagine that the other lenders might be eyei=
ng that claim greedily. If Revlon just=C2=A0doesn=E2=80=99t pay it, then th=
at=E2=80=99s $500 million more for the other lenders, and right now it=E2=
=80=99s not clear that Revlon needs to pay it.
