      People are worried about bond market liquidity
   =20
 =20
It=E2=80=99s back! Here=E2=80=99s  Bloomberg=E2=80=99s Katie Greifeld on th=
e Federal Reserve shrinking its balance sheet:Perhaps a harder question to =
answer is what shrinking the balance sheet will mean for already-fraught tr=
ading conditions in Treasuries. Liquidity in the $22 trillion market has de=
teriorated over the past few months, with the Bloomberg US Government Secur=
ities Liquidity Index -- a gauge of deviations in yields from a fair-value =
model -- hovering near the highest levels since March 2020.Fed officials ar=
e seemingly well-aware of the risk as the portfolio shrinks. The minutes fr=
om May=E2=80=99s meeting showed that several policy makers =E2=80=9Cnoted t=
hat the tightening of monetary policy could interact with vulnerabilities r=
elated to the liquidity of markets for Treasury securities.=E2=80=9DLayer i=
n the fact that capital requirements have kept the big US banks from adding=
 to market-making capacity in Treasuries over the past few years, and the o=
utlook appears dicey.=C2=A0You never hear this about stocks? Like, no one e=
ver says =E2=80=9Cliquidity in stocks is declining because big US banks don=
=E2=80=99t have much market-making capacity in stocks.=E2=80=9D Everyone ju=
st assumes that market-making in stocks is done by high-frequency trading f=
irms, and that they don=E2=80=99t carry much inventory overnight. If some i=
nvestor is selling stocks one day, then some other investor has to buy them=
:=C2=A0There is not a lot of capacity for stocks to be sold to a bank witho=
ut finding a real buyer, and if there are no buyers then the price goes dow=
n until there are. But I guess stocks are supposed to be more volatile than=
 Treasuries. Also to be fair the Fed wasn=E2=80=99t buying tons of stocks o=
ver the last decade; that does make things a bit weird.
