] In particular, the fact that tons of=C2=A0Musk=E2=80=99s=C2=A0followers a=
re bots =E2=80=94=C2=A070% of them, according to this estimate =E2=80=94 is=
 not inconsistent with Twitter=E2=80=99s claim that fewer than 5% of its mo=
netizable daily active users are bots, because Twitter=E2=80=99s metric of =
=E2=80=9Cmonetizable daily active users=E2=80=9D is *intended to exclude bo=
ts*. From the most recent 10-Q: =E2=80=9CWe are continually seeking to impr=
ove our ability to estimate the total number of spam accounts and eliminate=
 them from the calculation of our mDAU, and have made improvements in our s=
pam detection capabilities that have resulted in the suspension of a large =
number of spam, malicious automation, and fake accounts. We intend to conti=
nue to make such improvements. After we determine an account is spam, malic=
ious automation, or fake, we stop counting it in our mDAU, or other related=
 metrics.=E2=80=9D If 50% of Twitter accounts are bots, and Twitter knows i=
t and excludes those accounts from its mDAU count, then its metrics are rig=
ht =E2=80=94=C2=A0but it would still look, to Musk, like there are a lot of=
 bots.[2] The merger agreement does not say that. However, Twitter=E2=80=99=
s securities filings have for years said some highly qualified version of t=
hat:=C2=A0Its most recent Form 10-Q says =E2=80=9CWe have performed an inte=
rnal review of a sample of accounts and estimate that the average of false =
or spam accounts during the first quarter of 2022 represented fewer than 5%=
 of our mDAU during the quarter. The false or spam accounts for a period re=
presents the average of false or spam accounts in the samples during each m=
onthly analysis period during the quarter. In making this determination, we=
 applied significant judgment, so our estimation of false or spam accounts =
may not accurately represent the actual number of such accounts, and the ac=
tual number of false or spam accounts could be higher than we have estimate=
d.=E2=80=9D And the merger agreement contains a representation (Section 4.6=
(a)) saying that none of Twitter=E2=80=99s SEC filings =E2=80=9Ccontained a=
ny untrue statement of a material fact.=E2=80=9D If Twitter were *intention=
ally* lying about how many bots it had, that representation would probably =
be false, though given how qualified the statement is I think just getting =
it *wrong* would not falsify the rep.[3] See Section 7.2(b) of the merger a=
greement.[4] Section 7.2(a).[5] Section 6.4.[6] Section 6.11(a).[7] The law=
yers=E2=80=99 letter also threatens: =E2=80=9CAt this point, Mr. Musk belie=
ves Twitter is transparently refusing to comply with its obligations under =
the merger agreement, which is causing further suspicion that the company i=
s withholding the requested data due to concern for what Mr. Musk=E2=80=99s=
 own analysis of that data will uncover.=E2=80=9D But what do they think Tw=
itter is afraid of? If Musk=E2=80=99s analysis reveals that a lot of Twitte=
r accounts are bots, he doesn=E2=80=99t get to walk away from the deal. Pre=
sumably the implied threat here is =E2=80=9Cwe think you are not giving Mus=
k the data because you worry that he will find out that there are a lot of =
bots *and publicize his findings*.=E2=80=9D Which he certainly would!=C2=A0=
[8] Actually there are a few other=C2=A0important qualifications. In partic=
ular, Twitter doesn=E2=80=99t have to give him the information he asks for =
if it would =E2=80=9Ccause significant competitive harm to the Company=E2=
=80=9D or =E2=80=9Cviolate applicable Law or the provisions of any agreemen=
t,=E2=80=9D and Musk can=E2=80=99t use it =E2=80=9Cfor any competitive or o=
ther purpose unrelated to the consummation of the transactions contemplated=
 by this Agreement.=E2=80=9D=C2=A0
