-color: #ccc;">boasted publicly</a> that he violated a non-disclosure agree=
ment with Twitter by tweeting about Twitter=E2=80=99s bot methodology![7]<e=
m>=C2=A0</em>If you give him sensitive user data he is just absolutely goin=
g to tweet about it, and trusting his promises not to would be dumb. And if=
 he does break his promises, what can Twitter do? Sue him to call off the d=
eal? Twitter doesn=E2=80=99t want to call off the deal. Musk does!</p><p st=
yle=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Still, this pretext is better than Musk=E2=80=99s p=
retext, for at least three reasons:</p><ol style=3D"list-style-type: decima=
l; padding-left: 40px; margin: 16px 0;">=09<li style=3D"margin-bottom: 5px;=
">As closing conditions for the merger, representations are qualified by MA=
E, but covenants by =E2=80=9Cin all material respects.=E2=80=9D If Twitter =
does not comply with its covenants, Musk=C2=A0<em>can=C2=A0</em>walk away, =
so this makes for a good threat.</li>=09<li style=3D"margin-bottom: 5px;">T=
he representations are limited to what the merger agreement actually says, =
but this covenant =E2=80=94=C2=A0the one about furnishing information =E2=
=80=94=C2=A0is limited only by (1) Musk=E2=80=99s (and his lawyers=E2=80=99=
) imagination and (2) the somewhat fuzzy standard of =E2=80=9Cany reasonabl=
e business purpose related to the consummation of the transactions.=E2=80=
=9D[8] So Musk can ask Twitter, like, =E2=80=9Cgive me the cell phone numbe=
rs of every one of your monetizable daily active users so I can call them a=
nd see if they=E2=80=99re bots,=E2=80=9D and Twitter will have to decide if=
 that is reasonable, if it violates any laws, etc. If they say no, Musk can=
 disagree, and it might end up in court, with Musk having the ability to wa=
lk away if he wins. If they say yes, Musk can just keep asking for more thi=
ngs. =E2=80=9CTell us what all of your users were thinking about last Thurs=
day,=E2=80=9D why not.</li>=09<li style=3D"margin-bottom: 5px;">Because Mus=
k really has been talking about=C2=A0<em>solving=C2=A0</em>the bot problem,=
 and because this request can be characterized as helping him do that, it d=
oesn=E2=80=99t sound as much like a lie as his pretext does. =E2=80=9CAs Tw=
itter=E2=80=99s prospective owner, Mr. Musk is clearly entitled to the requ=
ested data to enable him to prepare for transitioning Twitter=E2=80=99s bus=
iness to his ownership,=E2=80=9D says the letter: If he=E2=80=99s going to =
clean up the bots, he needs information about the bots, and he is allowed t=
o ask for it now.</li></ol><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">I mean, to be clear=
, it isn=E2=80=99t=C2=A0a=C2=A0<em>good=C2=A0</em>pretext. It is, for insta=
nce, very hard to imagine that Musk=E2=80=99s banks are clamoring for detai=
led information about spam accounts to line up their financing; Twitter has=
 raised debt financing in the past with its existing bot disclosure. Nor is=
 it clear what Musk=E2=80=99s =E2=80=9Creasonable business purpose related =
to the consummation of the transactions=E2=80=9D is. And because it is so c=
learly part of Musk=E2=80=99s broader trolling operation, it is hard to ima=
gine him=C2=A0<em>winning=C2=A0</em>if this ends up in court: If he refuses=
 to close because Twitter won=E2=80=99t humor his bot-fishing expedition, i=
t seems unlikely that a Delaware court will side with him. But it does rais=
e the <em>risk=C2=A0</em>for Twitter,=C2=A0which gives him a bit more lever=
age to try to renegotiate the price. It is all going to get so much dumber.=
</p><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">In other Twitter M&amp;A news, on Friday t=
